{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491380"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:45:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:45:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"927"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/927"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.38,0.05,0.05,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104683"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/927"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87037"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1717"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34885"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34886"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104683"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with an episode of complete loss of vision affecting his right eye which has not resolved after 48 hours. He reports several prior similar episodes that resolved spontaneously within hours. His medical history includes a myocardial infarction and insertion of a drug-eluting stent. He currently takes aspirin, clopidogrel and nifedipine. On examination, he appears well. His blood pressure is 150/90 mmHg with a regular pulse of 94/min. Examination of his chest is unremarkable. His visual acuity in the right eye is Light Perception and the left eye is 6/6. He has a right eye relative afferent pupillary defect. He has a normal anterior segment examination. Fundoscopic examination of the right eye is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of his clinical presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic valvular disease","Carotid artery disease","Venous thromboembolism","Mural thrombus formation","Central retinal artery atherosclerosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe right eye fundus image demonstrates a right eye central retinal artery occlusion with a cherry red spot and retinal pallor indicating retinal ischemia. Additionally, there are visible cholesterol emboli (Hollenhorst plaques) which are pathognomonic for emboli from the carotid arteries and is the differentiating feature for the underlying cause of central retinal artery occlusion. The clinical scenario describes a complete central retinal artery occlusion with prior amaurosis fugax. The patient\u0027s presentation with recurrent episodes of transient vision loss that resolve completely is classic for amaurosis fugax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid artery disease\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s presentation. Atherosclerotic plaques in the carotid arteries can release cholesterol emboli that travel to the retinal circulation, causing transient or permanent visual changes. This patient has multiple cardiovascular risk factors (previous myocardial infarction, hypertension) that also increase his risk for carotid disease. The presence of Hollenhorst plaques on fundoscopy strongly supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic valvular disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause embolic phenomena, but typically these would be calcific emboli rather than cholesterol emboli. Additionally, there is no mention of a cardiac murmur or other signs of valvular disease on examination, making this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal artery atherosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to atherosclerotic disease within the retinal artery itself. While this can cause visual symptoms, it would not typically present with recurrent transient episodes as described here, nor would it explain the presence of cholesterol emboli seen on fundoscopy, which originate from a more proximal source.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous thromboembolism\u003C/strong\u003E does not cause ocular disease. Venous system thromboemboli cannot cause ocular venous disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMural thrombus formation\u003C/strong\u003E, typically occurring in the left ventricle after myocardial infarction or in atrial fibrillation, can lead to embolic events. However, these emboli are typically fibrin-platelet thrombi rather than cholesterol emboli. While this patient has a history of myocardial infarction, the characteristic appearance of cholesterol emboli on fundoscopy points more specifically to carotid disease as the source. Additionally, the patient is on dual antiplatelet therapy (aspirin and clopidogrel), which would reduce the risk of mural thrombus formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amaurosis fugax presents as transient monocular vision loss, often due to emboli from carotid artery disease.","Hollenhorst plaques (cholesterol emboli) visible on fundoscopy are pathognomonic for carotid artery emboli.","Patients with carotid artery disease often have other cardiovascular risk factors and comorbidities."],"references":["Tadi P, Najem K, Margolin E. Amaurosis Fugax. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2020 Jan [cited 2020 Nov 26]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470528/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87037"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"927"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15628"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20442"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15628"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b5163cdb-f16a-48ea-b8c9-1642b1086c54.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b5163cdb-f16a-48ea-b8c9-1642b1086c54.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":437}},{"type":"media","id":"20442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20442"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2atk78pL2Nt3ZwyJytaIrzN5I9vF56.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2atk78pL2Nt3ZwyJytaIrzN5I9vF56.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":437}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87037"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-03T19:59:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-03T20:00:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"927"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104683"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"update